  "issue_title": "Investigate slow Qwen3 model loading and warm weight behavior",
  "issue_body": "## Context\n\nDuring Jetson validation after PR #66, the `genie-ai-runtime` CLI path can take a long time to load Qwen3 weights, and the current `genie-claw` systemd setup may be preventing warm model-weight reuse.\n\nObserved CLI command:\n\n```bash\n/opt/geniepod/bin/jetson-llm \\\n  -m /opt/geniepod/models/Qwen3-4B-Q4_K_M.gguf \\\n  --chat --no-think -n 80 \\\n  -p \"Say hello from GeniePod in one short sentence.\"\n```\n\nRelevant output:\n\n```text\nFREE:            2658 MB\nModel file: 2381 MB\nLoading model...\n[gguf] Mapping 2381 MB...\n[gguf] CUDA mapped host weights at 0xffff09227000 -> 0x2040ae000\n[gguf] Loaded 2381 MB\n[engine] Context: 3939 tokens (auto-capped to 4096; memory cap 3939, model max 40960). Override with -c <N>.\n[kv_cache] Allocating fast pool: 276 MB (3939 tokens)\n[kv_cache] Allocating per-head INT8 scales: 8862 KB (36 layers \u00d7 2 K/V \u00d7 3939 ctx \u00d7 8 kv_heads \u00d7 4 B)\n[scratch] cudaMalloc(64 MB) failed: out of memory\nFailed to load model.\n```\n\nThe OOM is separate and can be worked around by stopping the rest of the stack or forcing a smaller context. This issue tracks the startup/load behavior and whether model weights are warm.\n\n## Suspicion\n\n`deploy/systemd/genie-ai-runtime.service` currently has:\n\n```ini\nExecStartPre=/bin/sh -c 'sync && echo 3 > /proc/sys/vm/drop_caches'\n```\n\nThat may help contiguous NvMap allocations, but it also intentionally evicts page cache before every runtime start. So even if the Qwen3 GGUF was warm, the service start path may force it cold again.\n\nThe warmup unit warms inference after the server starts; it does not preserve warm model weights if `drop_caches` runs first.\n\n## What to check\n\n- Compare `genie-ai-runtime` startup with and without the `drop_caches` `ExecStartPre`.\n- Measure whether `/opt/geniepod/models/Qwen3-4B-Q4_K_M.gguf` is actually warm in page cache before runtime start.\n- Confirm whether `drop_caches` is still needed for NvMap/contiguous allocation on Orin Nano, or whether it should be removed/conditional for `genie-ai-runtime.service`.\n- If possible, add a lightweight setup/debug command to report cold vs warm model weight state before startup.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- We know whether slow startup is caused by cold model reads, CUDA/NvMap mapping, allocator fragmentation, or memory pressure from the rest of the stack.\n- `genie-ai-runtime.service` no longer destroys useful warm model weights unless there is measured evidence that `drop_caches` is required.\n- The Jetson operator has a repeatable command to check model-weight warmness and startup timing.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-18T03:07:25.000Z",
